06391nam a22010095i 9783110311884DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)920798317  a97831103118847 a10.1515/97831103118842doi  a(DE-B1597)207866  a(OCoLC)890950471  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0020002bisacsh00aPartitioning the Soul :bDebates from Plato to Leibniz /ced. by Klaus Corcilius, Dominik Perler. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopoi – Berlin Studies of the Ancient World/Topoi – Berliner Studien der Alten Welt ,x2191-5806 ;v2200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPlato’s Divided Soul -- tParts in Aristotle’s Definition of Soul: De Anima Books I and II -- tWalking and Talking: Reflections on Divisions of the Soul in Stoicism -- tPartitioning the Soul: Galen on the Anatomy of the Psychic Functions and Mental Illness -- tParts of the Soul in Plotinus -- tIamblichus, Proclus and Philoponus on Parts, Capacities and ousiai of the Soul and the Notion of Life -- tOckham on Emotions in the Divided Soul -- tVirtual Presence: Psychic Mereology in Francisco Suárez -- tThe Faces of Simplicity in Descartes’s Soul -- tSpinoza on the Unity of Will and Intellect -- tThe Great Chain of Souls: Leibniz on Soul Unitarism and Soul Kinds -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDoes the soul have parts? What kind of parts? And how do all the parts make together a whole? Many ancient, medieval and early modern philosophers discussed these questions, thus providing a mereological analysis of the soul. Their starting point was a simple observation: we tend to describe the soul of human beings by referring to different types of activities (perceiving, imagining, thinking, etc.). Each type of activity seems to be produced by a special part of the soul. But how can a simple, undivided soul have parts? Classical thinkers gave radically different answers to this question. While some claimed that there are indeed parts, thus assigning an internal complexity to the soul, others emphasized that there can only be a plurality of functions that should not be conflated with a plurality of parts. The eleven chapters reconstruct and critically examine these answers. They make clear that the metaphysical structure of the soul was a crucial issue for ancient, medieval and early modern philosophers.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSoul. 4aPhilosophiegeschichte. 4aSeele. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aSoul.  ahistory of philosophy.  aphilosophy of mind.1 aBarth, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcilius, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcilius, Klaus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHankinson, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmig, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInwood, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohansen, Thomas K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarfík, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerler, Dominik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerler, Dominik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRozemond, Marleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmid, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id